Asexual galls
(

). Asexual galls develop on the underside of the leaf blade (

) (sometimes also on the upper side), have a slightly elliptical subglobular shape and are very small, reaching at most 1.5–2.0 mm in diameter when mature. Their external surface is glabrous, covered with short and more or less pointed cone-shaped tubercles uniformly arranged in a regular pattern (

). They are attached to the leaf by a thin, short stalk (

), rarely on the veins and the leaf does not show any mark on the opposite surafce indicating a gall is present beneath. Each leaf can contain up to ten galls.

Sexual galls
(

). 

The sexual galls develop on adventitious buds mainly on large oak trunks (

), often in groups of 5–12, sometimes solitary; they are unilocular (

), sessile, sub-ellipsoidal in shape (ovoid) with major axis length 2.0– 
2.3 mm
, minor axis 
1.8–2.1 mm
. During the short growing phase, they have a succulent texture, with conspicuous red, purple and light green colouration (

); their surface is granular, owing to the presence of a layer of large protruding cells (

), the walls often adorned with thin lamellae, vestiges of the transformed bud perulae (

); as they mature, the granulation is reduced by dehydration and the surface takes on a light brown colour and the walls become thin and coriaceous (

). Sexual adults emerge from a large lateral hole and the galls are not deciduous and remain attached to the bark for a few years. Fresh galls obtained in this study were compared with those that were collected by 
Gaicomo Mantero
in 
1909 in
Liguria
(
Genoa province
) preserved in ‘Cecidotheca italica’at the 
Botanical Garden of Padua
(

) (see “Additional material examined for morphological diagnosis”); both sets of gall were identical

.

sec.p:
The sexual generation galls develop in the spring (March–April) on the areas of the trunk with vigorous regrowth (
Fig. 9
). The small young galls develop from adventitious buds and quickly mature with the emergence of the males and immediately afterwards the females between the end of April and the first ten days of May. The old galls remain attached to the trunk for some time and young galls of the subsequent asexual generation are often found near to them. After mating the females oviposit into the tender young leaves; here the eggs remain quiescent until the onset of summer and in August the small galls of the asexual generation become visible. The galls grow and mature with the arrival of autumn-winter; when the host plant slows down its own vegetative cycle the galls remain fixed to the leaves and fall with them. The inducer wasps spend a long diapause in their larval stage in the leaf litter, then pupate and emerge either the following spring or two springs later.

