Molecular methods can also allow for pairing of currently unmatched sexual and asexual generations into a single species’ life cycle, given that both generations within a species have got identical (or nearly so) DNA sequences (

, 

, 

). Single-gene methods can occasionally fail, for example in closely related species complexes where hybridisation sometimes occurs (see 

), but a molecular approach whereby both mitochondrial and nuclear genes are used (as employed in this study) provides a more robust verification process. Molecular approaches to generation matching are also particularly useful in instances where adults of one generation are difficult to rear and only larvae of that generation are available for sequencing. This utility is demonstrated in this study and has also been previously demonstrated in a Nearctic 
Cynipini
species, 

Dryocosmus juliae

, whereby sexual adults and galls were matched to a recognised asexual gall morphology from which adults have not yet been successfully reared or formally described (

). However, ideally both experimental rearings and molecular data would be used for generation matching since the two approaches are complementary and mutually reinforcing as evidenced by this work.

The results of the present study and our recent studies (e.g., 

, 

; 

) show that much remains to be revealed about the life cycles of 
Cynipidae
, even in the Western Palaearctic where they are considered a relatively well studied family. Further study may lead to a reduction in the number of valid species as a result of life cycle closure since many species remain known from only a sexual or asexual generation, although the use of molecular data have shown that some sexual-only ‘species’ are actually complexes of multiple species inducing identical galls (

). In addition, new species likely remain to be described especially in southern and eastern regions (see for example 

), and many biological aspects of known species require careful further investigation.
